\lex -e
\ps gm
\de MIR.PFV
\seme mirative perfective
\gn -ए
\lg N
\com In the written language and in clearly pronounced spoken language, this suffix is clearly distinct from the contracted variant -ya of -eko [NPST.PRF]. The morphology is distinct in any variety, cf. e.g. the different negated forms -e-nʌ-ch-ʌ/-e-nʌ-th-yo (MIR.PFV) vs. -eko/-ya chʌin-ʌ/thi-en-ʌ (simple PRF). However, -ya may come very close to -e in fast pronunciation and is almost always transcribed as <e>, anyways, in the Chintang corpus, so be careful: most of the time <echa> represents a normal perfect and should thus be glossed -eko ch -a. The mirative perfect is only to be used when both pronunciation and semantics make it clear that it was intended.
\qst

