\lex -go
\morph -ko
\alt -ggo
\alt -o
\ps gm
\de NMLZ
\seme nominalizer; is suffixed to all parts of speech including verb forms to mark that they modify a following (mostly covert) referent
\gn एको; को
\lg C
\ex Paraya usiago maʔmice jamma Rai ta.
\exe Most people who died were Rais.
\exn प्राय: मरेका मान्छेहरू सबै राई नै थिए ।
\exsrc Story_chintang.015
\com This form is not a suffix by the criterion of host-selection (it can occur with nominals, verbs, and adverbs) but is still analysed as a suffix here because it can attach to true suffixes (which would otherwise be separated from their host from a morphological gap, e.g. in ba go-ce 'these'). The allomorph -ko appears optionally after -no [IND.NPST] and obligatorily after -beʔ [LOC], -iʔ [LOC], and the u-allomorphs of demonstratives (a-mmu-ko etc.). 
\qst

