\lex sakeũwa
\alt sakeũwã
\alt sakẽwã
\alt sakewa
\alt sakeuwa
\ps n
\de a.place
\gn साकेउँवा
\lg C
\qst Sakẽwa or, in other Kirãti languages, Sakela is also the name for the Udhouli and Ubhouli rituals traditionally performed when moving to the lowlands or highlands between seasons. In Chintang, rituals are performed at the Sakẽwa altar at the beginning of Wadhaŋmi. If there's a connection between Wadhaŋmi and Sakẽwa in other Kirãti groups, the word "sakẽwa" could first have been the name of the ritual and later been transferred to the place by metonymy.

